             ## SOURCE FILES

-            Read these pre-fetched Bluesky JSON files from data/bluesky/:
-            - data/bluesky/ai_announcements.json
-            - data/bluesky/llm_releases.json
-            - data/bluesky/model_discussions.json
-            - data/bluesky/ml_papers.json
-            - data/bluesky/karpathy.json
-
-            The Bluesky JSON structure is:
-            - posts[].author.handle (username like "user.bsky.social")
-            - posts[].author.displayName (display name)
-            - posts[].record.text (post content)
-            - posts[].record.createdAt (ISO timestamp)
-            - posts[].likeCount (likes)
-            - posts[].repostCount (reposts)
-            - posts[].uri (post URI for linking)
+            Read every JSON file under data/bluesky/. Two shapes appear:
+
+            1. searchPosts results (`ai_announcements.json`, `llm_releases.json`,
+               `model_discussions.json`, `ml_papers.json`):
+               - posts[].author.handle / displayName
+               - posts[].record.text / createdAt
+               - posts[].likeCount / repostCount / replyCount
+               - posts[].uri
+
+            2. getAuthorFeed results (`author_*.json` — one per researcher/lab):
+               - feed[].post.author.handle / displayName
+               - feed[].post.record.text / createdAt
+               - feed[].post.likeCount / repostCount / replyCount
+               - feed[].post.uri
+               - Skip items where feed[].reason is set (those are reposts).
+
+            If a JSON file is empty, malformed, or contains an `error` key
+            (e.g. upstream rate-limit / outage), skip it silently and note
+            the gap at the bottom of the digest under "Source Notes".

             To create a link: https://bsky.app/profile/{handle}/post/{post_id}
             Where post_id is the last segment of the uri (after "app.bsky.feed.post/")
